  "prompt": "Will operating systems in the future support Braille displays?",
  "response": "As of now, many operating systems already support Braille displays, and it's highly likely that future operating systems will continue to support and improve compatibility with these devices. Operating systems like Windows, macOS, and various Linux distributions have been integrating accessibility features, including support for Braille displays, to cater to users with visual impairments. These features are often enhanced through updates, reflecting the ongoing commitment to accessibility.\n\nFuture advancements may include more seamless integration, broader support for different Braille display models, improved user interfaces, and potentially new features leveraging AI to enhance the experience for visually impaired users. Additionally, as the demand for inclusive technology grows and awareness increases, manufacturers and developers are likely to prioritize and innovate within the realm of accessibility tools.",
